snippet.textDisplay:
Mike - next time you have to do this and aren't sure if you have enough time - take some of your brownie batter and put it in a ramekin - then microwave it while the rest bakes normally. If whats left works out time-wise in the oven - then just serve the brownies - but if not, you have the microwave version to maybe save the day. --- you also could opt to just put a very thin later at the bottom, and then maybe slice out of squares or circles and stack them for final plating (a thinner brownie would cook faster, but 2 or 3 can still be stacked for thickness/ portion size)

Also - near the end, you could have taken some edge pieces (the most baked areas like corners) and put them on a plate - microwaved them a bit, poured sauce. Its not going to look as good as what you originally intended to do - but it will look like its on purpose. Something less good looking - but on purpose - will still come across as a better presentation than something that is obviously the unintended product. -- Just throw some mint on it at the end like Ben does. lol.

Think of it like fashion. If you have holes in your jeans - you look homeless - if you have holes in your jeans on purpose - you look trendy. There are plenty of fashion choices that just look outright stupid - but this is less the case if the person knows how it looks, and CHOSE to make it look that way rather than accidentally looking like a visual assault. Art is subjective - cooking is an art-form.

"In the eggnog, I'm not getting Christmas...."


To any American watching, (who likes eggnog) just got triggered! (eggnog used to be a Christmas item, then moved to holiday time. Some stores have it in by thanksgiving... again an American holiday). I honestly don't have different foods I eat from thanksgiving vs Christmas.
... I think I just bake more cookies and other sweets (puddings -American pudding, chocolates, candies, cakes, etc. for Christmas than thanksgiving (which I normally make pies for).

snippet.textDisplay:
First of all, as an American..we invented the Martini during the prohibition era.
The main ingredients for a Martini are gin and vermouth.
You can have a hundred different varieties depending on the garnish.
The James Bond movies were the used vodka are completely wrong and were dictated by Smirnoff brand because they sponsored the films.
Shaken not stirred is an abomination. You only shake cocktails that include fruit juice.
If You shake a Martini it will be cloudy.
Anything else is just a cocktail.
Serving it in a Martini glass doesn't make it a Martini.
